context: By <a0_0><b4_0>1988<b4_0/><a0_0/>, industry observers stated that the NES's popularity had grown so quickly that the market for Nintendo cartridges was larger than that for all home computer software. <a1_0><b5_0>Compute<b5_0/>!<a1_0/> reported in <a2_0><b6_0>1989<b6_0/><a2_0/> that Nintendo had sold seven million NES systems in 1988, almost as many as the number of <a3_0><b7_0>Commodore 64s<b7_0/><a3_0/> sold in its first five years. "Computer game makers [are] scared stiff", the magazine said, stating that Nintendo's popularity caused most competitors to have poor sales during the previous Christmas and resulted in serious financial problems for some.
